<p>Vague predictions <em>are</em> falsifiable; they&#8217;re just less likely to be wrong. And my argument isn&#8217;t that 5% is too high or too low, it&#8217;s that it&#8217;s arbitrary. If a study works only at 6% should we sentence people to death because we&#8217;re missing the other 1%. (Actually, what really happens is that people fake the data to get it over the hump, as a recent paper proved.) Evidence doesn&#8217;t have clean lines between true and false; we depend on the situation to decide how strong our standards should be.</p>

